    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-08-19T14:24:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-08-19T14:24:00-05:00" n="1139"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1139">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">251G.51G22/8–1754: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Vietnam</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d1139fn1">Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MR2"
                            >McClintock</persName>. Repeated for information to Paris as 624, to
                        Manila as 642, to Tokyo as 373, and to Hanoi as 215.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-08-19T15:24:00-04:00"
                            >August 19, 1954—3:24 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>652. We seriously concerned with report set out your 613.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d1139fn2">Dated Aug. 17, <ref target="#pg_1951">p.
                        1951</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>You are instructed immediately to secure an audience with <persName
                        corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> and say that US having responded with such
                    speed and in terms such magnitude his request for transportation in lifting
                    evacuees from Tonkin is dismayed at apparent complete lack proper facilities for
                    reception these refugees upon their arrival in South Viet Nam. Inform <persName
                        corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> US while glad give aid Free Viet Nam must
                    condition its aid upon performance by Vietnamese Government. You should orally
                    suggest to Prime Minister that Phuoc who now responsible Vietnamese refugee
                    program should be given powers of requisition of civilian labor and transport
                    facilities, an adequate staff and under direct instruction Prime Minister full
                    support from General <persName corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName> and Vietnamese
                    National Army.<note n="3" xml:id="d1139fn3">In telegram 654 from Saigon, Aug.
                        20, <persName corresp="#p_HDR1">Heath</persName> reported that on Aug. 19,
                        prior to the receipt of the Department’s telegram, an Embassy official had
                        discussed the refugee problem with <persName corresp="#p_NDD1"
                            >Diem</persName>, and that it seemed unwise to raise the question again
                        immediately. <persName corresp="#p_HDR1">Heath</persName> also reported that
                        the first U.S. naval ship with 2,000 refugees had docked on Aug. 19.
                        (251G.51G22/8–2054)</note>
                </p>
                <p>You likewise authorized inform General <persName corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName>
                    serious view we take this situation and read to General <persName
                        corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName> or Deputy text instructions sent <pb
                        facs="0580" n="1962" xml:id="pg_1962"/>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> to make an immediate <hi
                        rend="italic">démarche</hi> with French Government on this problem. This
                    text provided in next succeeding telegram.<note n="4" xml:id="d1139fn4">The
                        instructions sent to Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DCD1"
                            >Dillon</persName> are contained in telegram 625 to Paris (653 to
                        Saigon), Aug. 19, <ref target="#d1140">
                            <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>
                        </ref>. In telegram 693 from Saigon, Aug. 24, <persName corresp="#p_HDR1"
                            >Heath</persName> reported that an Embassy official had read the message
                        to Acting Commissioner General <persName corresp="#p_DJ1">Daridan</persName>
                        on Aug. 21. <persName corresp="#p_DJ1">Daridan</persName> had characterized
                        the message as “pretty strong.” (251G.51G22/8–2454)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
